14:04.577 --> 14:08.981 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Between now and Election Day, we
will strive
to go beyond the headlines to
explain what's

14:09.015 --> 14:10.917 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
happening and why.

14:10.950 --> 14:15.421 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Lisa Desjardins kicks it off
with a closer
look at Donald Trump's recent
statements on

14:15.455 --> 14:17.256 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Russia and Ukraine.

14:17.290 --> 14:20.493 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: First, here's
what Donald
Trump said.

14:20.526 --> 14:24.063 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It was over the weekend about
Ukraine and
Russian President Vladimir
Putin.

14:24.097 --> 14:26.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DONALD TRUMP (R), Presidential
Candidate:
You know, I have my own ideas.

14:26.499 --> 14:28.968 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He's not going into Ukraine, OK,
just so you
understand.

14:29.001 --> 14:30.703 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He is not going to go into
Ukraine.

14:30.737 --> 14:32.371 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
All right?

14:32.405 --> 14:33.706 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You can mark it down, you can
put it down,
you can take it any way you
want.

14:33.740 --> 14:35.108 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GEORGE STEPHANOPOULOS, ABC News:
He is already
there, isn't he?

14:35.141 --> 14:37.143 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DONALD TRUMP: Well, he is there
in a certain
way, but I'm not there.

14:37.176 --> 14:38.811 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
You have Obama there.

14:38.845 --> 14:43.216 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: Critics point
out Vladimir
Putin and Russia are in Ukraine
now.

14:43.249 --> 14:45.084 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Let's look at some facts.

14:45.118 --> 14:49.589 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We're talking about two critical
areas, Crimea
on the Black Sea, and the
Donbass region in

14:49.622 --> 14:50.823 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Eastern Ukraine.

14:50.857 --> 14:52.525 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
First, Crimea.

14:52.558 --> 14:58.131 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In 1991, as the Soviet Union
dissolved, Ukraine
and Russia became separate
nations.

14:58.164 --> 15:05.271 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Voters in Crimea were split, but
they voted
54 percent for Ukrainian
independence.

15:05.304 --> 15:11.010 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Tensions built, protests
erupted, and, in
2014, Ukrainians pushed out a
pro-Russian

15:11.043 --> 15:13.212 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
government in Kiev.

15:13.246 --> 15:19.118 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In Crimea, unidentified forces,
no flags on
their uniform, fomented an
uprising and a

15:19.152 --> 15:23.623 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
referendum going the other way,
in favor of
Russia.

15:23.656 --> 15:28.227 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Then Russia annexed Crimea, with
international
outcry, but little bloodshed.

15:28.261 --> 15:33.699 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Meanwhile, in the Donbass
region, war broke
out, as militant separatists
took over towns

15:33.733 --> 15:36.335 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and fought Ukrainian government
forces.

15:36.369 --> 15:38.838 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That's a war that continues
today.

15:38.871 --> 15:42.175 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The key question, what was
Russia's role?

15:42.208 --> 15:47.547 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We know Russian troops stationed
in Crimea
did seize key positions there,
and Russia

15:47.580 --> 15:51.417 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
confirmed that it sent soldiers
on intelligence
missions in Donbass.

15:51.450 --> 15:56.322 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Ukrainian government says
Russia has done
far more, sending more soldiers
and weapons.

15:56.355 --> 15:59.125 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, this brings us back to Mr.
Trump.

15:59.158 --> 16:04.897 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Here is his clarification on his
words that
Putin isn't going into Ukraine
from a speech

16:04.931 --> 16:06.699 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
yesterday.

16:06.732 --> 16:12.905 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DONALD TRUMP: But a couple of
papers said,
Donald Trump doesn't realize
that the Crimea

16:12.939 --> 16:14.340 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
was already taken.

16:14.373 --> 16:18.477 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I know it exact -- two years
ago, approximately,
OK, approximately?

16:18.511 --> 16:21.113 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It was taken during Obama's
watch.

16:21.147 --> 16:26.219 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: In other words,
Trump argues
that he knew about Crimea, but
he wasn't talking

16:26.252 --> 16:30.356 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
about Crimea when he spoke of
Putin and Ukraine.

16:30.389 --> 16:31.557 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
That is notable.

16:31.591 --> 16:34.026 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It would be a profound shift in
U.S. policy.

16:34.060 --> 16:40.533 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Obama administration sees
Crimea and Eastern
Ukraine as sovereign parts of
Ukraine, and

16:40.566 --> 16:43.669 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
accuses Putin of violating
international law.

16:43.703 --> 16:48.341 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's a sharp turn in policy, as
is something
else Trump said last week.

16:48.374 --> 16:51.844 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He was asked if he'd remove U.S.
sanctions
against Russia.

16:51.878 --> 16:52.845 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
His answer?

16:52.879 --> 16:53.846 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DONALD TRUMP: We will be looking
at that,
yes.

16:53.880 --> 16:55.615 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
We will be looking.

16:55.648 --> 16:59.051 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: And that is a
change from
where Trump was in 2014, when he
said this

16:59.085 --> 17:01.287 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
about punishing Russia over
Ukraine:

17:01.320 --> 17:02.889 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
DONALD TRUMP: We should
definitely bee strong.

17:02.922 --> 17:06.058 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
We should definitely do
sanctions, and we
have to show some strength.

17:06.092 --> 17:11.597 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: One final piece
of context
about Trump's campaign chairman,
Paul Manafort.

17:11.631 --> 17:16.502 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Manafort advised the campaigns
of Viktor Yanukovych,
the pro-Russian leader of
Ukraine, who was

17:16.535 --> 17:18.738 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
deposed in 2014.

17:18.771 --> 17:22.441 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Manafort has said he was pushing
Western interests.

17:22.475 --> 17:27.480 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
As we look closely at the
candidate's words,
the Trump campaign insist Mrs.
Trump's overall

17:27.513 --> 17:32.251 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
belief is that the U.S. should
be less involved
in the entire region.

17:32.285 --> 17:38.925 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Lisa Desjardins for the "PBS
NewsHour."

17:38.958 --> 17:49.001 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now a look at how
required
math classes may factor into the
academic

17:49.035 --> 17:53.105 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
success or failure of high
school and college
students.

17:53.139 --> 17:58.077 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Hari Sreenivasan has the story
as part of
our weekly education series,
Making the Grade.

17:58.110 --> 18:02.615 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
ANDREW HACKER, Professor
Emeritus, Queens
College: Words and numbers, we
use them both.

18:02.648 --> 18:04.483 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We use them for different
reasons.

18:04.517 --> 18:07.553 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Even if you
aren't going
to be an engineer, getting
through high school

18:07.586 --> 18:09.555 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
or college means getting through
math.

18:09.588 --> 18:10.556 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MICHAEL GENAO, Student: Why do
we need to
take all these math classes?

18:10.589 --> 18:11.924 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's not necessary.

18:11.958 --> 18:15.494 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's not needed for what we are
actually learning.

18:15.528 --> 18:20.066 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Andrew Hacker,
the college
professor teaching at the front
of this classroom

18:20.099 --> 18:22.034 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
at New York's Queens College,
agrees.

18:22.068 --> 18:27.540 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANDREW HACKER: The goal is to
have everybody
do a full menu of mathematics,
up to and including

18:27.573 --> 18:28.708 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
calculus.

18:28.741 --> 18:32.912 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I don't see any rational
reason for this
at all.

18:32.945 --> 18:37.984 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What I'm suggesting is that at
least there
should be other options,
alternatives, instead

18:38.017 --> 18:41.387 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of this rigid math curriculum
for everyone.

18:41.420 --> 18:46.225 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Minimum
requirements for
math are different across the
country, but

18:46.258 --> 18:50.496 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
many states today demand getting
through the
quadratic equations and two
years of algebra

18:50.529 --> 18:56.469 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to graduate high school, and
most college
degrees also require some math
credits.

18:56.502 --> 19:01.140 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Hacker writes about this
perceived disconnect
between academic requirements
and the everyday

19:01.173 --> 19:04.610 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
needs of graduates in his recent
book, "The
Math Myth."

19:04.643 --> 19:08.681 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ANDREW HACKER: It's actually
several myths.

19:08.714 --> 19:15.888 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One of the myths is that every
one of us is
going to have to know algebra,
geometry, trigonometry

19:15.921 --> 19:21.193 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in the 21st century, because
that's the way
a high-tech age is going.

19:21.227 --> 19:22.728 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's a total myth.

19:22.762 --> 19:28.401 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
At most, 5 percent of people
really use math,
advanced math, in their work.

19:28.434 --> 19:33.172 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: You're also
drawing a distinction
in your book between mathematics
and arithmetic.

19:33.205 --> 19:34.173 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Explain that.

19:34.206 --> 19:35.408 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ANDREW HACKER: Yes.

19:35.441 --> 19:37.977 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
We use math, the term,
indiscriminately.

19:38.010 --> 19:43.282 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think we teach arithmetic
really very well
up through grades, let's say,
five or six.

19:43.315 --> 19:45.084 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
We do it.

19:45.117 --> 19:49.922 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But then, instead of continuing
with arithmetic
to what I would call adult
arithmetic, or

19:49.955 --> 19:55.461 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
sophisticated arithmetic, we
immediately plunge
people into geometry and
algebra.

19:55.494 --> 20:00.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, as a result, Americans are
really quite
illiterate in terms of numbers.

20:00.699 --> 20:02.802 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Hacker's
alternative?

20:02.835 --> 20:04.136 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Teaching what he calls numeracy.

20:04.170 --> 20:10.209 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ANDREW HACKER: It's income per
hour, essentially,
per person.

20:10.242 --> 20:12.678 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Is Norway well ahead of the
United States?

20:12.711 --> 20:13.679 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
OK.

20:13.712 --> 20:15.614 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Let's continue with that.

20:15.648 --> 20:18.818 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Where he
focuses on developing
his students' mathematical
literacy by giving

20:18.851 --> 20:20.986 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
them some real-world perspective
on the subject.

20:21.020 --> 20:26.792 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANDREW HACKER: How to read a
corporate report,
how to look at the federal
budget, how to

20:26.826 --> 20:33.732 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
parse the numbers on the
campaign trail, how
votes are cast, and how many
seats are won,

20:33.766 --> 20:38.971 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
all sorts of assignments like
this, which
only require arithmetic, but
adult arithmetic.

20:39.004 --> 20:43.609 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: A political
scientist by
training, Hacker and his
assertions have predictably

20:43.642 --> 20:47.613 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
put college and high school math
departments
across the country on the
defensive.

20:47.646 --> 20:50.282 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
DIANE BRIARS, President,
National Council
of Teachers of Mathematics: We
need algebra

20:50.316 --> 20:55.821 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
as a basic way of making sense
of our world.

20:55.855 --> 20:59.225 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Many mathematical relationships
are described
using algebra.

20:59.258 --> 21:03.963 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Diane Briars
is president
of the National Council of
Teachers of Mathematics.

21:03.996 --> 21:08.634 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We chatted with her on nearly
her home turf,
the National Museum of
Mathematics in Manhattan.

21:08.667 --> 21:16.175 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DIANE BRIARS: Algebra gives us a
way of representing
relationships in general, so
that we can reason

21:16.208 --> 21:20.146 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
about them in the general case,
instead of
specific cases.

21:20.179 --> 21:27.419 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Algebraic equations and
expressions are also
ways of describing patterns that
we may see

21:27.453 --> 21:28.921 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and differences between those
patterns.

21:28.954 --> 21:31.557 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ANDREW HACKER: This is put about
by the mathematicians.

21:31.590 --> 21:35.828 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think they have to say this:
Mathematics
trains the mind.

21:35.861 --> 21:38.998 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
There's no evidence for this
whatever.

21:39.031 --> 21:41.734 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Mathematics trains the mind for
mathematics.

21:41.767 --> 21:46.071 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Hacker thinks
math is a
powerful divider of high school
success.

21:46.105 --> 21:50.476 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
A number of students succeed and
move onward,
while a sizable fraction do not.

21:50.509 --> 21:57.049 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANDREW HACKER: One out of every
five of our
citizens has not finished high
school.

21:57.082 --> 21:59.585 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We have a 20 percent dropout
rate.

21:59.618 --> 22:02.421 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's one of the highest in the
developed world.

22:02.454 --> 22:08.527 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the chief academic reason
for this dropout
rate is algebra in the ninth
grade.

22:08.561 --> 22:11.964 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: The fail rate
is something
Diane Briars doesn't dispute.

22:11.997 --> 22:21.106 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DIANE BRIARS: The fact that
failing algebra
I as a ninth grader is -- makes
a student

22:21.140 --> 22:25.778 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
more likely to drop out is a
huge problem
that the mathematics education
community is

22:25.811 --> 22:28.814 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
actively engaged in.

22:28.847 --> 22:34.353 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One of the ways we're addressing
that is by
building a stronger foundation
in K-8 mathematics.

22:34.386 --> 22:38.824 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
With a more solid conceptual
understanding
in K-8 mathematics, students are
going to

22:38.857 --> 22:41.961 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
be much better prepared to be
successful in
algebra I.

22:41.994 --> 22:45.531 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: But Hacker
says the math
failure is greater than just
high school.

22:45.564 --> 22:51.036 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANDREW HACKER: Forty-seven
percent of people
who start a four-year college do
not get a

22:51.070 --> 22:52.071 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
degree.

22:52.104 --> 22:55.674 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That's a very high dropout rate,
close to
half.

22:55.708 --> 23:02.248 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Chief academic reason, freshman
math course,
which people fail and don't make
up.

23:02.281 --> 23:05.251 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And why don't we ask ourselves,
look at the
talent we're losing.

23:05.284 --> 23:10.723 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Why are the
institutions
in high school and in college
structured the

23:10.756 --> 23:13.726 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
way they are to emphasize math,
as we do today?

23:13.759 --> 23:19.231 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANDREW HACKER: Here's the big
word I always
hear: Let's be rigorous, the big
R. Let's

23:19.265 --> 23:24.136 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
be rigorous, so let's make
everybody coming
into community college pass a
stiff algebra

23:24.169 --> 23:25.137 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
test.

23:25.170 --> 23:27.673 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That shows how rigorous we are.

23:27.706 --> 23:29.508 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Same thing at a higher level.

23:29.541 --> 23:35.781 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If you take Princeton, Stanford,
Yale, they
want virtually all of their
incoming students,

23:35.814 --> 23:44.290 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
except for athletes and a few
alumni children,
to have an SAT score on math of
at least 700.

23:44.323 --> 23:45.291 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
That's very high.

23:45.324 --> 23:47.126 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That's the top 7 percent.

23:47.159 --> 23:48.127 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Why?

23:48.160 --> 23:50.195 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We're Princeton, we're rigorous.

23:50.229 --> 23:54.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And in the name of rigor, we
have this irrational
math barrier.

23:54.500 --> 23:58.170 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Diane Briars
agrees with
that too, but only up to a
point.

23:58.203 --> 24:02.308 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DIANE BRIARS: You can argue
that, for some
of them, that requirement may
have been put

24:02.341 --> 24:08.280 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
there to ensure that they filter
people out.

24:08.314 --> 24:16.121 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
On the other hand, being able to
be facile
with symbols and equations is
necessary for

24:16.155 --> 24:17.990 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
a number of trades.

24:18.023 --> 24:24.330 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For example, the electricians
union has passing
a course in algebra I as a
requirement for

24:24.363 --> 24:26.131 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
an apprenticeship program.

24:26.165 --> 24:29.735 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: So both sides
agree that
the formula for the right amount
of math isn't

24:29.768 --> 24:31.537 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
optimal.

24:31.570 --> 24:35.307 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Figuring out the right equation
may be one
of the first major problems for
new graduates

24:35.341 --> 24:36.542 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
everywhere.

24:36.575 --> 24:41.914 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," I'm Hari
Sreenivasan
in New York.

24:41.947 --> 24:49.988 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Stay with us.

24:50.022 --> 24:56.061 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Coming up on the "NewsHour": a
Midwest mayor's
plans to build trust between
